			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Traps, Locks, and other things that go bump in the night.<a name="53528"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Jul 24 04 12:13 AM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>I have tried to put together some of the information spread out through the forums as an aid to new bards. Please provide feedback as appropriate so that it is complete.
<br />

<br />
This is a guide to some of the secondary skills available to a bard. I will try to cover what the skill is used for, how to use it, and how to practice it. I assume that you are familiar with making macros and mapping them into hot buttons; if you are not, there are several guides on EQDiva telling how to make them.
<br />

<br />
<b>Sense Trap</b>
<br />
The sense trap ability helps locate traps by turning you in the direction of the nearest one. You use the skill by mashing the button. You have to train a point in pick locks at level 15 and it caps at (level)*3 with a max of 120.
<br />

<br />
Sense Trap is the first of the skills I will talk about that benefit from being auto-trained; that is by being activated as a side effect of some action you would be doing anyway like moving or twisting (see below). Sense Traps can be auto-trained anywhere; in fact, the best places are those zones with no traps (you exercise the skill for looking even if you don’t find a trap) and you won’t end up running into a just sensed trap by mistake.
<br />

<br />
<b><i>Auto-training</i></b>
<br />
The basic idea of auto-training is to tie a skill attempt to something you would be otherwise doing. There are two classic approaches for bards: movement key hot-buttons and song macro extensions. In addition, there is the semi-automatic, caster favorite: fishing.
<br />

<br />
The movement key approach can be used by all classes. You create a hot-button with the skill you want to activate and then map it into the same key-stroke that is used for a movement key (forward, turn-right, turn-left). You do this by opening options window and clicking on the Keyboard tab; then choose Macros from the category selector; last click on the alternate column for the hot button you want (it should contain “------“) and press the movement key—it will show up as red to show the key is mapped to two or more functions, which is what you want—to cancel the alternate mapping, click on the alternate mapping for the hot button and press the escape key.
<br />

<br />
With the movement key approach you can either drag the skill button from the abilities page of the action window or create a multi-line macro that drives the skill and drag the macro button from the socials page. The macro approach gives you the ability to add more than one skill to the same hot button (buttons being a very scarce resource for a bard); however, it comes at a price: only one macro can run at a time and this macro can interfere with your song macros during a twist.
<br />

<br />
The second approach is to add the skill attempt to the end of one of your song macros; for instance, if you have Song 1 as “/stopsong” then “/cast 1”, you can add another line “/doability 3” (if the skill you want is in the 3rd spot of the abilities page). If you are going to do this, it is best to choose songs you twist during down time (forage doesn’t work in combat; sense trap turns you around if it finds a trap; sneak and hide are just funky in combat).
<br />

<br />
The fishing approach is simple and gives you the sense that you are accomplishing something useful while practicing skills. You make a macro that starts with “/autoinventory” and “/doability #” for the fishing skill. After that you can add up to 3 more lines with whatever else you want to train. This is particularly nice for things that would be annoying using the other methods, such as, sneak and hide. Unlike the other methods, you need to mash the macro button for each attempt, but that requires minimal attention, allowing you to listen to music, finish War and Peace, or chat up that Vah Shir with the particularly soft fur.
<br />

<br />
<b>Disarm Trap</b>
<br />
The disarm trap ability allows you to attempt to disarm a trap that you have located. You use the skill by mashing the button while being near the trap. You have to train a point in Disarm Trap at level 20 and it caps at (level +1)*5 with a max of 120.
<br />

<br />
Disarm Traps can be auto-trained anywhere; in fact, the best places are those zones with no traps since you get the skill for trying, even if there is no trap around. I know it doesn’t make sense, but no one said it had to.
<br />

<br />
<b>Pick Locks</b>
<br />
The pick lock ability allows you to open any lock with a rating at or below your skill. You use the skill by clicking on your set of lock picks to place them on the mouse cursor and then clicking on the locked item. You have to train a point in pick locks at level 10 and it caps at (level)*3 with a max of 125 (you may want to wait until level 11 since the lowest level locks are at that level).
<br />

<br />
The only way of training lock pick is by successfully picking a lock; that is, if you can’t pick the lock, you get no chance of a skill-up. There are several good places to train; for low skill levels there is a locked door (second on left) on the first level of Befallen and the elevator lock into Paneil (I use this, it is a lozenge shaped rock on the path to the right of the entrance into Paneil, has no roaming monsters to contend with, and is a quick click to open/click to close). There is also a lock in the entrance to Plane of Tranquility (a book on a table), which higher level characters speak fondly of.
<br />

<br />
<b>Sense Heading</b>
<br />
Sense heading is an interesting footnote in the lore of EQ.  Characters now start at level 200, which is the maximum.
<br />

<br />
Back in the bad old days, before there was a compass on the user interface, we had to mash the Sense Heading button to obtain a guess at what direction we were facing (higher level meant better guess)—actually we watched the directions of cloud movement or dropped swords (point north). Along came the compass, but sense heading determined the accuracy of the compass (with low sense heading, it would swing wildly). Now that Sense Heading starts at max; it has no effect on game play at all.
<br />

<br />
<b>Alcohol Tolerance</b>
<br />
Alcohol Tolerance is a somewhat bizarre skill. Many people see this as a totally useful skill; however, there have been reports of some traps and other attacks that make you drunk and that high tolerance protects you from the bad effects. You don’t have to train a point in swimming to start and it caps at (level +1)*5 with a max of 200.
<br />

<br />
You train by drinking alcohol. If you drink in moderation, you remain functional; however, if you drink too much, you start weaving and become badly impaired (gee, who said EQ isn’t like real life). 
<br />

<br />
<b>Begging</b>
<br />
Begging is the act of asking an NPC for money. You use the skill by mashing the button while targeting an NPC (preferably one that won't kill you if it gets mad, like someone's pet or an NPC in PoK). You don’t have to train a point in Begging to start and it caps at (level +1)*5 with a max of 200.
<br />

<br />
Begging is actually useful--of course you could make a few silver pieces an hour with high enough skill. However, remember that, when the beg attempt fails critically, you end up angering the NPC; this can get you killed. There is a Gates of Discord quest that requires a high begging skill (Breakdown in Communication #3: Riwwi).
<br />

<br />
Many people think that begging provides a way to get aggro and use it during fights; however, here is something from Valya:
<br />
<blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">Steel Warriors folks did a controlled experiment on Beg as agro. It appears that all a beg failure does is make a formerly non-KOS mob KOS, it does not have an agro component per se. Many people do try to use it as a &quot;taunt&quot; but I'm convinced, at least, that this is simply a waste of time.</span></blockquote>
<br />

<br />
<b>Fishing</b>
<br />
Fishing is fishing, what else is there to say. You need a fishing rod in your primary hand and bait in your inventory. You don’t have to train a point in Fishing to start and it caps at (level +1)*5 with a max of 200.
<br />

<br />
In addition to fish, fishing pulls up trash and the occasional tradeskill item (such as seaweed). Also, you use the fishing skill to make special lures and de-bone fish in a tackle box; I have no opinion on the use of lures, but fish bones can be made into very nice darts by a fletcher.
<br />

<br />
<b>Swimming</b>
<br />
Your swimming skill affects the speed with which you swim (big surprise there). It is a semi-passive skill (whenever you swim, it is used automatically). You don’t have to train a point in swimming to start and it caps at (level +1)*5 with a max of 200.
<br />

<br />
There are many descriptions available on how to practice swimming (swimming into corners, singing our level 16 water breathing song, etc.); however, they all boil down to “swim”. My own favorite is to find an open body of water and auto-circle swim while listening to Led Zeppelin and reading EQ Diva.
<br />

<br />
<b>Forage</b>
<br />
Forage gives you a chance to find food or other stuff lying around on the ground (or floating in the water for that matter). You have to train a point in forage at level 12 and it caps at (level +1)*5 with a max of 55.
<br />

<br />
Although you can always just mash the button when you want to forage something, it gets real tired, real fast. Forage is another skill that benefits from being auto-trained. The only difference is that forage is probably a skill you want to have going all the time, even after it is fully trained.
<br />

<br />
If you create a macro for forage (or add it to a song macro), you can use the two lines: “/autoinventory” and “/doability #” to automatically put away what you find. However, what I do on my bard and ranger is have separate Forage and /autoinventory hot buttons; I do this to avoid interference with my attack and song macros (nothing is worse than having an attack/song not start because you just turned right and the silly forage macro is still running).
<br />
</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
